Development of Grocery Stores in the Modern World
Throughout history, the wealthy have always had more luxuries than the lower class. They have luxuries in not just designer items but services that make their life much more efficient. The sociologist Max Weber would refer to the development of services as rationalization, which is when emotional decisions replace efficient procedures that make items more accessible for some consumers but, in turn, dehumanize the people who work for these corporations. Through the growth of rationalization in the modern world, companies that rely on consumers must also evolve. This growth can be shown through limited-item grocery stores developing into million-dollar corporations. To do this, grocery stores have implemented rationalization by having certain arrangements of items, consistent training, and new-age technology that adapts to consumers who are making them more money. Since adding these systems, it has affected the working class because they are the workers being dehumanized and turned into machines since that is the most consistent service.
 Many people feel the need to get things done fast to keep up with the fast-paced life in the US but cannot afford services that will allow them more time to focus on their careers. Some grocery stores have developed so people do not need to walk inside the store to buy items. Wealthy people would rather pay someone to get an item directly than walk into a store to find it themselves. Grocery stores now have adapted to the people who want this leisure by creating grocery delivery, curbside delivery, and personal food shopping services. These services allow the wealthy to pay to get items more quickly to live a leisurely life, while the lower class must adapt to providing these services.  
People still choose to go inside the grocery stores or cannot afford these luxury services, so, through rationalization, they have used people's predictability to set up their stores in the same arrangement. All stores in a specific corporation are set up the same way, so it is more convenient for consumers to go through them regardless of their area. They also have items such as cleaning supplies and drugstore items, so consumers only need to go to one place for everything. This accessibility allows customers to navigate the store quickly and find all the necessary items, enabling corporations to make more money from consumers by adapting to them. For example, people who need a dairy or meat item when going grocery shopping, stores set up those items to be placed in the back of the stores, people must walk through the aisles to get to the item they are searching for. Having to walk through makes them buy more because they see items through their walk, and do not even consider needing them until they see them. Once people finish shopping, they must go to checkout, which is set up so consumers can buy more. There are always small, cheaper items such as gum or a soda that are easily accessible while the customer is checking out, which makes them consider needing them as well. All these set-ups throughout the store are purposely in place to get more customers to subconsciously buy more items, which allowed grocery corporations to grow.
Another aspect of rationalization in grocery stores is that all workers are trained in the same way to allow consistency for consumers. This training can dehumanize working-class people by making them all act the same way. Through training courses, they are taught to act always of service to customers, specifically answer phones, and be in a specific uniform. Having to act the same robotic way towards every customer takes away from the personable experience lost through rationalization. Many consumers enjoy the reliability of getting in and out of the stores with no unexpected scenarios, but that is not naturally realistic in life. Naturally, nothing can be predicted entirely, but through the modern world, rationalization has made unexpected obstacles to getting something done much less likely, and even workers with strict training are not doing well enough.
Even employees are not efficient enough for people anymore, they have adapted to better technologies. Introducing new technologies, specifically self-checkout, has made even buying items at the store more efficient but takes away from human jobs and the personability behind them working. Now, with the establishment of grocery delivery services, people limit their interaction with other humans who are just robots working for them. People in higher classes use this type of service the most because they can pay more for a more efficient process. While the lower classes cannot pay for these efficient services, they must be the ones who do them.
Through analyzing rationalization being used for the growth of grocery stores it is shown how there are many advantages for wealthy people but disadvantages for those part of the working class. Overall, even though rationalization has made the modern world much more efficient, it has also turned the working class into machines.

Leadership: Final Paper
The third lesson I learned, was that leadership is a collaboration and a process. A major thing I learned from Leadership for a Better World by Susan R. Komives was that leadership is not a position that someone with power or money has to gain more power over people. Instead, leadership is a process of learning about yourself while collaborating with others. This lesson ties to the previous lessons learned about becoming more self-aware about one’s strengths and weaknesses and creating a concrete connection between leaders and followers. In this book, Komives further explains this through the Social Change Model of Developmental Leadership. With this model, social change was explained to me as people learning about themselves, their society, and the group they are a part of to comprehend how they can cooperate to achieve a goal. 
At the beginning of the semester, I viewed leadership as a position that people of power or a large amount of money have. I believed leaders were more like managers that assign certain tasks to people to achieve their goals. By taking this course, I have gained more knowledge about what leadership is, who can be a leader, and the different ways to become a better leader. Leadership in itself is not a position held by someone with power or money. It’s also not a manager using people to complete a goal. Instead, leadership is a process in which someone acts as a teacher or guide to help others alike achieve a common goal. This leader, or group of leaders, can be anyone for any amount of time. In the book A Long Walk To Water, written by Linda Sue Park, the main character is a young boy named Salva Dut. His story represents how leadership takes courage and motivation to create change, even if it is from a young boy in a difficult situation. Aside from positive leaders, there are some negatively motivated leaders. However, if you can connect with others and guide them to a common goal, you are technically a leader.
One thing I have learned about leadership this semester based on experiences outside of the classroom is that good leader and follower relationships are essential. While being a full-time student at UNCW, I decided to look for employment near campus to obtain some extra income. One day, my roommate and I decided to visit a local bakery. We walked in, only expecting to pick up some pastries. However, we were able to apply and were hired that same day. The first day, I noticed how nice the manager was and how the other employees interacted with each other. Overall, I believed it would be a lovely place to work. However, I soon learned that wasn’t entirely true. Although nice, the manager was very disorganized when it came to paperwork, schedules, communicating, and leading his workers. This created a very negative connection between him and me. Due to this, I decided to find work elsewhere. I soon applied for Starbucks and received an interview within the week. During the interview, I discovered the works are labeled partners rather than coworkers, how the business is run, and how I would be a part of this corporation. I was also informed that my manager is a good example of a leader. Although she manages the store and does tell people how to work, she also leads her partners, answers any questions, creates connections with almost every customer, and will work alongside the other partners to help alleviate the workload and any stress. 
My biggest takeaway from Leadership 211 is that leadership is not a position, it’s a process. I first believed that leadership was a position or role that one takes to lead others. With this course, I learned that is not true. Although a leader tends to be the one person who takes initiative to lead and seems to control a group of people, they are guided by their followers. Leaders must go through a process of becoming self-aware and understanding their goals, strengths, weaknesses, and how they lead. They also learn to understand and connect with others to create a group of loyal and supportive followers who can help them become a better leader. Leadership is not a position. Leadership is a process of growing and connecting with other people to reach a common goal.

Durkheim vs. Awkward Silence
Sometimes, awkward and uncomfortable experiences or beliefs that connect a group of people, are seen as normal for other groups, or even society as a whole. Having a group of people come together and share values, beliefs, ideas, and morals attitudes is seen as a relatively positive concept. However, there’s always a negative, or a less pleasant side. For some groups, this may be morals that other groups or society as a whole don’t agree with. For others, it might be awkward or uncomfortable shared experiences that influence and alter their beliefs. In this case, why do these experiences continue to happen if they are so awkward and uncomfortable? 
A shared belief among socially anxious people and introverts, is that silence is awkward. This belief can be shared with other people as well, including extroverts. It’s something that happens frequently between strangers, friends, or family. However, awkwardness and being uncomfortable are just a normal feelings that humans encounter every so often. These awkward silences typically last for only a few short moments or even a few minutes. They also happen commonly between strangers you most likely won’t interact with again. Overall, it might be an irrelevant moment in most people’s lives. 
Most of the time, awkward silence happens with strangers. Since they are unfamiliar, this interaction allows the people to create their first impressions of each other. In some cases, such as having an interview or meeting with someone significant, having this awkward silence could be detrimental. First impressions of strangers are typically unimportant, however, in those cases they are seen as crucial. This first interaction with important people can determine if you are able to obtain things such as being hired for a certain job or possibly new connections that could be helpful in times of need. There are multiple other instances where people encounter awkward silences with strangers. 
Most people will avoid awkward situations or situations that make them uncomfortable. An example, for some people might avoid getting on a crowded elevator full of strangers. On the other hand, sometimes you are talking with someone on the elevator and having a private conversation, but someone joins. Neither you nor the person you are talking with want this stranger to listen to this conversation, so you both stop talking. This creates an awkward silence. This stranger might feel most awkward because they unintentionally interrupted your conversation. 	
On another note, some people don’t like awkward silence because they feel the need to fill that space. Some extroverts feel the need to constantly have people to talk to. When they are still around people, but unable to do that, it makes them uncomfortable. This also applies to the person in a group who tends to be the entertainer. In the group, they are usually the extroverted person who is always telling jokes to make everyone happy and makes light of most situations. When they are around a new group of people or in a setting that requires silence, it makes them uncomfortable because it’s not what they are used to.
These moments typically don’t last very long and seem insignificant in our overall life. Most people may not pay any mind to it. However, for those who do pay more attention to it, it can be difficult. Introverts and socially anxious  people typically stay within their friend groups or familiar people, but at times they want to interact with new people. When they start talking to new people and the conversation begins to shift to awkward silence, it affects them the most because they were actively trying to meet new people and it didn’t go over well. For extroverts and entertainers, the silence is something that creates discomfort because it’s something they aren’t used to. Overall, this awkward silence just creates an uncomfortable situation that most people would much rather avoid.
David Emile Durkheim was a French sociologist and philosopher who was born on April 15, 1858 and died on November 15, 1917. He was known as the father of the French School of Sociology for incorporating empirical study with sociological theory. In 1983, he presented the concept of collective consciousness (also known as collective conscience), in his book “The Division of Labor in Society.” This is a concept that describes a set of beliefs, ideas, and moral attitudes that are shared within a common group or society. The collective consciousness is manifested by society through collective representations. Collective representations are symbols, artifacts, or narratives that embodies the beliefs, ideas, or moral attitudes of a group or society as a whole. 
Collective representation can include symbols such as a wedding ring, artifacts such as football, or narratives like “the customer is always right.” For a group of people with social anxiety or who are introverted, they dislike silence in social settings. This is because the silence creates a feeling of anxiety, discomfort, and awkwardness. These experiences of encountering strangers, meeting new people, entering crowded spaces, or wanting to interact with others but not being able to, happens all the time. Since those experiences kept happening, socially anxious and introverted people, as well as extroverts and entertainers, started to view silence as awkward. This led to the narrative that silence is awkward continues to present itself whenever a situation becomes too quiet and the interaction between people is interrupted or disappears.  
Through the collective consciousness, the narrative of silence being awkward has presented itself in many people’s lives. This begins when one person experiences silence and describes it as awkward. Then, one person encounters another person, or other people with the same experience and belief. What started as a singular, personal experience, is now recognized as a more common event. When this group comes upon conclusion or opinion about the event, it becomes a collective representation of silence.
Sometimes, what connects a group of people is something that is seen as negative or unpleasant. Commonly amongst socially anxious people and introverts, they experience and dislike awkward silence. These instances can happen with friends and family, but most frequently, its between strangers. There are situations where the awkward silence lasts a few moments and seen as irrelevant later-on. Examples include meeting someone for the first and only time, getting on an elevator with other people already on it, or going to a social gathering and making small talk. However, there are situations where an awkward silence could detrimental. Examples of this would be meeting someone important or having a job interview. Along with socially anxious people and introverts, some extroverts and entertainers of the group find silence to be awkward as well. Most common situations for them would be talking to new people and not being able to hold a conversation, or they are in a setting where they must be quiet. This silence makes them uncomfortable because it’s not what they are used to. Durkheim’s collective representation explains this narrative that silence is awkward amongst the group of socially anxious people, introverts, extroverts, and entertainers.

Men Are Keeping “The Beauty Myth” Alive
	How do you define beauty? There are many different ideas and views of what beauty is in society. You can look at any social media platform for example and see that there is a beauty standard that is in place, but the real question is, do you know who put these beauty standards in place? Men did. The reason that women feel the need to be beautiful even in today's society is because of men and how they viewed women in the earlier ages. 
Women became subjected to the “beauty myth” back in the late 1800s because of men and their views on women. Back then the only use for women was to be a housewife to a man, and if they did not succeed at finding a husband they would most likely they would die. Women were unable to support themselves on their own back then because as you know it wasn’t until the early 1900’s that women gained the rights to own land and get jobs. Because of this, women felt like they needed to compete with others to gain the most attention from the men. The problem caused by this is a separation that was beginning to form between women everywhere. Everything was always a competition to them due to the view of the men.
This led women to believe that their value was based on their looks and how men viewed them rather than their personality, talents, and knowledge. The women who were not considered as beautiful as others by men then developed some-what of a fear towards the other women. We can understand this because women would be forced to compare themselves to others. This caused a lot of the competition we still see to this day between women in many different fields. If a woman is the face of a business she usually has stereotypical beauty standard features. This is because it is what the business knows will draw in the most people and make the most money.
A lot of the women who believed that they would not equate to anything because of their looks would develop mental disorders such as depression and anxiety. They would have to face this every day and have this constant feeling of judgment over them knowing that they would not be “good enough” for the men. Mental disorders then led to physical disorders such as anorexia and bulimia. Women would starve themselves or throw up their food just so that they would not gain weight. They would wear uncomfortable corsets and clothing that made their features more prominent all so that men would see them as “beautiful”. Women would go through all of these hardships just to please men, why? Because it is what they had to do to survive back then, but people today still show signs of this in a lot of different ways.
Although the world has gone through a lot of change since these times, the one thing that has not changed is the value of beauty to women and men. For example, in society as a woman, there are times that I feel threatened by other women because of their looks. As we have studied, sociologically a man’s brain is formed to look at women they find beautiful and turn away from the ones that they do not find beautiful. This impacts women’s everyday lives as they may feel that they have to impress people with their looks. Being a woman in society can cause a lot of pressure because of the ideals for women that men have kept up and even the new ones they have created. 
We had this one discussion in class where we looked up attractive men versus attractive women. We noticed many differences between the pictures that showed up for each of them. The main differences were that there was more of a variety of men than there were of women and the men were wearing more professional clothes and expressions. While the women were wearing revealing clothing with more subtle submissive expressions. This shows that there are certain stereotypes forced into women’s heads for what “beautiful” is. This is because men have institutionalized their thoughts and ideas of “beautiful” women.
Another very clear modern-day example of this is shown throughout social media. When you post a picture of yourself do you post the worst one or the best one? Everyone posts their best photos in hope that people will be appealed to them. As we learned, the views that others have on us have a very high effect on the way that we perceive and look at ourselves. If someone comments on a picture that you posted saying something rude or vulgar then you are more than likely to either delete the comment or the picture. We do this because what other people say and do towards us either boosts or plummets our self-esteem. This is why we see people, especially famous women, posting only the very best photos of themselves. 
Another very prominent yet concerning example is pornography. Pornography is one of the most money-making media productions to this day. Meaning, it gets a lot of viewers and reactions. This created another factor of the “beauty myth” that women now have to be worried about. This is another example of how men sexualized women by making them vulnerable to their sense of sexual self-worth. Because of this, women feel like they need to perform like the people they see when doing sexual things. This is such a bad thing that is being placed into women's heads all over the world today because of how much the media is portraying it. For example, I will e scrolling on my phone through Instagram and then randomly there is just a half-naked woman on my screen that is reposted by a page run by men. I have seen this happen to many other people as well. That just shows that men are trying to advertise women’s bodies to their own benefit.

The Similarities and Differences of Harari and Sociologists
           Harari states that all different species and societies are formed around beliefs and traditions that have been around for centuries and they have distinct social systems. However, the social systems aren’t something that is genetic is based on what communities you are brought up in. In chapter 6 he compares how the Germans have been organized into six different systems which were the Hohenzollern empire, Weimar Republic, The Third Reich, German democratic republic, the federal republic of Germany, and the Democratic reunited Germany. In some of these communities, the beliefs were all different because they were made up of different thoughts and ideas and that’s why they ultimately separated. They still all somewhat have kept to their original routes and ways even though the Germans went through that much change.
 He also compared primates to how some of human society’s work and to evolve, for example, a gorilla pack is more like a dictatorship where there is a leader that is above all the others and then the females follow behind. Then Chimps work together more like a democratic group where there is open to more possibilities to teamwork and not just being ruled by one and less violence because if a gorilla is challenged by another they make that problem go away more so with violence. The main point in that is within those two groups things may change and rules may change but the way of doing things will stay the same.
Harari's arguments also connect with Emile Durkheim's view on the collective consciousness which is a set of shared beliefs ideas and moral attitudes which operate as a unifying force within a society. While over time in different society’s although things change and all different communities keep up with time and technology they are always going to hold on to the strong beliefs and being set in certain ways and that’s why Harari’s and Durkheim views are similar and can be compared to each other. 
           Harari states that in any civilization or group, anything can be manifested into a common belief in a society’s system especially if the society is for it. His statement says “Human groups are defined more by the changes they undergo than by any continuity, but they nevertheless manage to create for themselves ancient identities thanks to their storytelling skills.” Similarly, Durkheim, believes that all societies have the collective concessions to enforce and bind individuals to the moral order that a society creates. These relate to each other because even a single person within a community must follow the traditions and beliefs that have been set up by that certain society. In almost any society there is always some form of consequence for disrespectful acts, and the severity of your actions is based on where you are and what rules have been put in place.
             Another comparison between Harari and Durkheim is when Harari discussed different anthems. He stated that if you take out the specific name of the country in almost every anthem it would be hard to tell where and what regions the anthems come from. Most anthems have to do with pride and loving and supporting their communities but some people take their county pride and use it to be harmful and negative towards others.
            This relates to Durkheim because he believes that the social is something that we collectively create together by a shared sense of reality, morality, and identity-based on commonly shared experiences. Both of these people believe that communities need to feel a, sense of unity together to thrive, even if it means being prideful.
           When discussing religion Harari seems to shift the meaning of religion more so on modern-day religion and how some religions have matured around science and technology. He believes that in modern-day society religion had created three types of problems. The first being technical problems which would be problems caused by natural events and how back in the day you would go to the church and ask the priest how to handle stations. Most would tell you to turn to prayer and wait for God to solve the problems instead of action themselves. The second problem is policy problems which would come into conflict with problem-solving especially if you are in a very strict religion. Say if you have a medical problem but your religion restricts you from reaching out for modern-day help because it would cause you to potentially “sin” against your religion, would you choose to adhere to the policies that your religion has put in place or take care of the problems head-on and risk possibly sinning. The third problem that he states is identity problems which can be scary because a lot of times people will hide behind religion or use it as a mask even for things that have been done wrong. Like someone using religion as an excuse to back up a wrongdoing no matter how evil it is.
           Unlike Harari, Alexandra Maryanski and Johnathan H. Turner believe that religion was important to society because it was necessary to bring people together based on a collective belief created/manifested by a group of people who value their religion and the rules of it. Because of a stronger development of emotions, the range that people feel about their specific religion becomes greater, therefore, they needed something to believe in and base their hope in. This contrasts with what Harari said because he doesn’t quite get the importance of religion and how people like to stay on the path and follow the “rules and guidelines of their own religion. He thinks that people like that need to try and find a way to evolve their religion with modern-day technology and medicine.
           While Maryanski and Turner believe and understand that religion is different in every society and community because of the beliefs that have been followed by that group they respect that and embrace it. They also believe in the ability to form relationships became very prevalent as the capacity for symbolic thought increased. They seemed to understand the critical role that religion played in the forming of civilizations more than Harari did. 
Another example of a contrast between the two is when Harari talks about how some traditions from different religions can make many people behave unfairly and cruelly to others to the point of committing harmful and potentially causing death towards others just because they don’t have the same beliefs and views. This is one of the reasons he sees religion as a problem because it can blindside so many people from realistic thinking. He states that “when it comes to solving rather than stoking the global problems of the 21st century they don’t seem to offer much.” So, Harari is basically is saying that people who run to religion as a safety net are just really avoiding the bigger problems at hand.
However, Maryanski and Turner believe that if a group of people from a community come together and share a belief such as using prayer as a form of protection, then they will be able to collectively create a “protective power”. This is considered collective effervescence, which is the feeling of the energy that someone gains from doing something as a whole. They state that religion is the “soul of society” because it has the ability to bind societies together to form a community. They can go through this not only when they feel protected by their god, but just doing something as a community can give this effect.
In conclusion, the points made by Harari throughout this book were very interesting. Upon reading this I was faced with many points that made me stop and think for a second. When Harari talks about how the future is going to be based on artificial intelligence and technology is very scary for someone who is rising up into those future generations. As he said, many jobs will be at risk which could cause a downfall in the economy. He really makes you sit back and look at the bigger issue with today’s society and that the world needs to focus on evolving as a whole to solve today's problems. Not saying that everyone needs to be the same but the world needs to come together and help each other out instead of being so against one another and being more open-minded.

Racism and Black Stereotyping within the Media 
This paper will seek to supply an argument that explores the issues in today’s media and how the media fails to properly provide black people with the attention and resources they need. For generations racial bias has affected the way America is run, who holds the power, and whose face will be shown to the public masses. This generalized bias has slowly formed white privilege over the years, and it is clear within America’s media who the main addressed audience is truly meant to be.

He has also written many books such as: Homo Deus: A Brief History of Tomorrow, Sapiens: A Brief History of Humankin, and 21 Lessons for the 21st Century. A key theme in his belief system is that human society has mostly been driven by our capacity to believe in fiction. Our collective belief in fictions, which we give meaning to, establishes a cooperative basis for existing as a community. Among his bestselling books is 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, which goes into greater detail about this key belief among other things. In 21 Lessons for the 21st Century Harari explains his opinions on various social dynamics and dilemma’s using historical and sociological evidence. While some of his points complement the writings of the authors who we read in class, Harari holds some opinions, which outlined in his book, contradict certain writings. In other words those opinions hold little sociological ground. Through deeper analysis we can conclude to what extent the content of this semester corroborates Harari’s opinions or whether it does at all. More broadly, we can determine, of his opinions, what contradicts or complements what we have read and learned in class. The conclusions of this analysis will serve as a good foundation for identifying where sociology played a role in the formation of his ideologies. 
Class systems have existed throughout time as a means to subjugate individuals through diminishing their worth and propping up a minority as a result. These systems sow inequality into a community which yields a hierarchical placement of people in the upper, middle or lower classes. The Caste System in India works similarly, you are placed, from birth, in a caste which automatically assigns characteristics to you accordingly. These characteristics are not equal to others, but determine your freedom and worth throughout your life. Ancient Greece and Rome had similar systems but like India’s they were blatant at keeping people down. In the United States, a kind of caste system exists but is not as obvious. Gregory Mantsios explains in his essay, “Class in America”, Americans are too afraid to distinguish the economic differences between their fellow citizens and the power of oppression in the class system largely keeps people in the class they were born into. The class a person is born into affects their life more than they know, and their unwillingness to recognize it propagates the reach and longevity of the system. This inequity takes two prominent forms, power and wealth, which are the mechanisms used to either give or prohibit the assumption of power. It is almost as if the country is a large company with a few very powerful and rich executives with most others serving as worker drones. Yuval Harari’s arguements, in part 4 of his book called Truth during the Post-Truth chapter, complement Mantsios’ analysis. In this chapter Harari explains that humans have always been living in a post-truth age, this is in line with his key belief that humans naturally believe falsehoods or fictions. Fake news if you will is necessary for classism to work, instilling false beliefs in a lower class can garner submissiveness and compliance. The American Dream is a prime example of how hope and fiction collide to produce a misguided but effective belief for the lower class to cling to. The dream itself states that anyone can achieve monetary success so long as they putforth the necessary effort. This is provably false, statistically and sociologically, it can be observed that not anyone can achieve success due to barriers like race, creed, economic satus, and a host of other variables. It is conveneient a lie however, because many people believe it and as such comes a variety of other sub beliefs that reinforce the class system. Beliefs like, the United States fosters an even playing field and no one can have too much money if they earned it working hard. Harari’s post truth argument also finds an important role in rendering Americans ignorant of the facts. Words like socialism and communism get used interchangeably by politicians despite being different ideologies, so as to scare Americans into believing the U.S will slip into communism should policies be enacted to give the middle and lower classes more or even as I see it. By falsely claiming basic quality of life policies for average Americans are akin to socialism or communism creates a negative association and infringes on the misguided, inherent, belief that everyone should make it on their own, in effect reinforcing the class system. In part 4 of his book Yuval Harari’s writings about post-truth and fake news serve as a foundation for allowing what Gregory Mantsios described in his essay about class in America. False ideals and fictions believed by the public supported and continue to support the class system in the United States by obscuring individuals perception and understanding.
A civilization is defined by Merriam-Webster as, “the condition that exists when people have developed effective ways of organizing a society and care about art, science, etc.” It seems from the definition that we as a collective of civilizations each with our own cultures, values and appeciations. At one time there existed merely one civilization of humans on earth. A small tight-knit community of people who shared common beliefs and acted their individual roles to help better the community. However, over time that civilization has grown exponentially and branching wildly in varying directions. Through this, it has become many distinct civilizations existing with each other but not exactly together. Harari argues in the civilizations chapter that we emerged from one and remain one, where it concerns human civilization. He claims that we are one civilization, something which might have been true thousands of years ago but as the world became more complex people divided themselves into smaller groups effectively making new ones. Each country is like its own civilization and because each has it own set of values, beliefs, et cetera, when they collide with others conflict can emerge in the form of xenophobia or war. It can be observed that when differing beliefs come together, each end will mostly try to rein supreme, which means they not only hold on to their beliefs but actively advocate for it over others. Many Americans, for example, fear immigration because they believe members from a civilization merging with theirs would infringe on or change the ideals they subscribe to. In our race and ethnicity module, Tomas Almaguer describes in his essay, the process of racialization. A process in which a group will ascribe ethnic or racial characteristics and identities to a group that they do not belong to themselves. Almaguer describes that Puerto Ricans and Mexicans had preconceptions of eachother according to the way race is defiend in those countries. They had taken to establish a conception based on more than that which they have been exposed to in their country. I think this contradicts what Harari presumes about civilizations because there appears to be no global lens through which to look. Although Harari argues that we are all members of the same civilization, we do not acknowledge each other like we are members of the same community, something that is integral to existing as one. 
Yuval Harari’s book 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, outlines many interesting opinions and highlights some observable facts within society. Many of his points seem to rest on sociological ground as well as statistical ground. His post-truth argument is especially interesting as it has a significant role to play in both small and large things. Its application to class in America bolsters Gregory Mantsios’ overall point that Americans do not realize the rampant inequity that plagues their country and creates an uneven playing field. However, not all of what Harari says complements what we have learned in class. COVID-19 and Its Negative Impact on Individuals Working Identities
	What are the most terrifying aspects of a pandemic? Initially, nearly all individuals will not hesitate to simply answer the above question as the possibility of becoming deathly ill, and even dying. Although the previously mentioned consequence of a pandemic is indeed terrifying, there are numerous other aspects of widespread diseases that can be very detrimental to human life as well. During the Coronavirus pandemic that the world is currently still facing, many challenges have arisen that affect people's everyday lives. The COVID-19 virus has proven to be very injurious to human lives in relation to their health, their finances, their labor, and much more. Throughout this paper I will discuss how the Coronavirus pandemic estranges individuals from their labor, fully destroys people’s relationship with their work, and can even harm a person's overall identity. 
	In class, we educated ourselves about capitalist societies in module seven. Throughout this module we read two discourses about humans in relation to these societies. In the writing, “Estranged Labor,” Karl Marx does an in-depth analysis about how labor in a capitalist society can be alienating for the worker in numerous aspects. Through the action of labor, workers can be isolated from the product, the process, each other, and themselves. The individual worker does not possess the product that is being produced, and therefore the more that they make, the less they actually own and the more segregated they become. In addition, the worker is solely performing the labor as a mechanism to survive and not for their personal contentment. This idea of labor being forced is also explained in “The Spirit of Capitalism and the Iron Cage” by Max Weber. Weber elucidates how people rationally devote their entire lives to making money, which expands upon how the labor merely serves the purpose of providing individuals with revenue. Since the labor is not voluntary, the worker remains unsatisfied and is alienated from the process. The forced labor can also estrange people from their own bodies and their human potential because their life activity is only a manner to physically exist. Finally, there is also the potential for the worker to become isolated from other workers in capitalist societies. Marx explains how this separation from each other occurs due to the competitive manner and the breakdown of labor in this economic system.
	This complex alienation that workers face occurs naturally in a capitalist society. Therefore, the detachment is already present within working citizens' lives. However, the estrangement becomes exaggerated and worsened through the presence of a crisis, such as a pandemic. The COVID-19 virus has been extremely damaging to human life in relation to their labor. This virus has been researched and was discovered to be spread from person-to-person through respiratory droplets. Due to this, the most efficient way to prevent the virus from rapidly spreading during the early stages of its emergence was to shut down unnecessary industries and restrict individuals from leaving their own homes. Therefore, this led to the forced shutdown of some companies and the failure of other businesses because they could not make enough profit to survive. The pandemic led to a record number of people becoming unemployed, more than ever before.
Numerous studies have been conducted that show the implications of this virus on the world. One of these studies is titled, “Experiences of Latinx Individuals Hospitalized for COVID-19, A Qualitative Study” and was written by thirteen certified researchers. This inquiry interviewed sixty citizens of Latin America, both male and female, to divulge how the Coronavirus pandemic directly affected these individuals. This investigation revealed that only 9% of the people were able to work from their houses, only a fifth of them were able to get money for a leave due to illness, and nearly 40% of them lost their job entirely due to the pandemic. In addition, of these individuals who lost their jobs and had to adjust their work environment, slightly more than 70% of them were deemed essential workers. Aside from numerical discoveries from the examination, the information also concluded that the COVID-19 widespread disease generated economic fears and disadvantages, social drawbacks, and labor issues (Cervantes et al. 1). The social downsides described in this article are a result of humans being forced to remain in their own homes. The forced social distancing, due to this virus, prevents individuals from interacting and leads to them becoming extremely isolated. Although not all of this isolation is related to labor, it still significantly impacts people and their connections to other humans, society, and even their own self-perception. Together, these implications can inflict damage upon a person’s overall identity. 
The above study performed in Latin America also unveils the effects from the Coronavirus specifically in relation to labor. The individuals in this inquiry experienced estrangement from their career, impacts on their relationship with their work, and consequences on their overall identity as well. The approximate 10% of people who continued working, but solely from home, experienced increased isolation from their co-workers due to the transition from in person employment to online employment. This isolation is added onto the previous segregation these people already faced, as described by Karl Marx. The nearly 20% of workers who received paid leave, as well as the 40% who lost their jobs entirely were fully stripped of the chance to form a relationship with their labor. In addition, having no occupation takes away an individual's ability to rationally devote their life to working, as described in “The Spirit of Capitalism and the Iron Cage” by Max Weber. Together, the increased alienation and unemployment then go on to harm an individual's overall identity. This is because they are no longer able to achieve a level of occupational status, which is the social ranking that derives from the labor one does. 
Another study conducted in relation to COVID-19 also demonstrates how the illness leads to complications between an individual and their relationship with their labor. This analysis is titled, “Forecasting major impacts of COVID-19 pandemic on country-driven sectors: challenges, lessons, and future roadmap” and was written by seven reliable researchers. The findings of this article reveal how the virus has been brutally challenging for citizens of the world by specifically examining the effects of the disease on India. The main challenges revealed through the article are economic damages, the shutdown of education centers, disaster in the healthcare industries, harm to international and local businesses, and impairment to the transportation, power, and oil industries (Kumar et al. 20-21). The damages done to all of these industries and aspects of life can be unified through the common theme of isolation. Shutting industries and education centers down leads humans to become segregated from other individuals, as well as aspects of their own life, such as their education and work. In addition, all of the harmful economic effects and the effects on businesses have led industries to fail and shut down. The article even states that, “Due to maintaining social distancing, the sales of the industry stop and all the companies are facing financial loss and closure” (Kumar et al. 9). This shows how the Coronavirus has caused companies to cease to function and individuals to lose their jobs. As previously mentioned, when individuals no longer have a profession, they also no longer have the chance to maintain a relationship with their labor. The elimination of this occupational relationship, as well as the greatly increased alienation from their coworkers, harms a person's social identity. 
However, the forced shut down of businesses not only takes people away from their own careers, but it also takes them away from other businesses. This then ruins their opportunity to go out and spend their money at these places. Throughout module seven, we learned about commodities in addition to humans' relationship with their labor. Commodities are essential to society because they captivate people and provide them with a motivation for their labor, which also shapes the productive and consumptive social world humans reside in. Commodities also give people a chance to develop their own identities, by allowing them to purchase materials that supply their life with meaning. However, in order for these commodities to exist there must be both a workplace and workers to produce them. Therefore, when businesses shut down and people lost their jobs due to the Coronavirus, the number of commodities diminished also. This directly impacted both individual human identities, as well as society as whole.
A third study conducted by qualified researchers reaffirms the harm done by the pandemic. This examination is titled, “Association of job loss, income loss, and financial burden with adverse mental health outcomes during coronavirus disease 2019 pandemic in Thailand: A nationwide cross-sectional study” and analyzes the effects of the Coronavirus on Asia. For this particular investigation, the researchers examined nearly 2,500 adults who were actively employed with full time jobs during the shutdown of the nation. The conclusions of the study were summarized by the loss of professions, income loss, and financial issues due to the outbreak of the disease. The conclusions continued on to prove how these economic complications then went on to create higher levels of stress, anxiety, and mental health problems in individuals (such as depression). The analysis directly states that “participants who reported losing their job had 51.9%, 56.9%, and 84.7% prevalence rates of depressive symptoms, anxiety symptoms, and perceived stress… income loss showed a slight association with depressive symptoms” (Ruengorn et al. 4). This quotation from the study discloses how individuals' mental health was harmed as a direct result from the elimination of a relationship with their labor. Overall, this shows how when a person is severely alienated from their work and loses the association they have maintained with their labor, their health suffers as a result. When a persons’ mental health is diminished their quality of life is also harmed, which can alter their self-perception and overall identity as well. 
Therefore, the Coronavirus pandemic has been proven to estrange individuals from their labor, fully destroy people’s relationship with their work, and even harm people's overall identity. Although the above studies were conducted by examining individuals in Thailand, India, and Latin America, the damage done to the people within these locations resembles the destruction done to the rest of the world as well. This detriment has stemmed from the shutdown of nations throughout the world, which has led to changes in work environments, destruction of companies, and more unemployment than ever before. These alterations have caused people to become more isolated from numerous aspects of their work, such as their co-workers and the process of their labor. People who fully lost their jobs no longer have the opportunity to have a connection with their occupation and as a result have had impacts on their identity as well. The negative implications from COVID-19 on peoples working identities can then change the way people feel about themselves and adjust the way they act in society, which will further impair aspects of the social world humans reside in down the road. Pandemics have much more harmful characteristics than the simple health consequences they provide. The Coronavirus, as well as other widely spread diseases, can harm individuals' identities, economical aspects of the world, and socialization within the world as well.

According to Susan Averett, a journalist with the Journal of Human Science in 1996, they “investigate income, marital status, and hourly pay differentials by body mass (kg/m2) in a sample of 23- to 31-year-olds drawn from the 1988 NLSY”. They have used this research to show that “obese women have lower family incomes than women whose weight-for-height is in the "recommended" range “. This is an example of how the beauty myth has affected society. It shows the difference that these beauty standards make between the weight classes in our society. The article also shows that “there is some evidence of labor market discrimination against obese women”. 
	This article shows the effect the beauty myth had on teens in the late 80s stating that “ Eating disorders (such as anorexia nervosa and bulimia) is a major social problem in the United States” having estimates such as ranges of “1 to 4 percent of the female population” for anorexia nervosa. There have also been higher estimates for bulimia nervosa “as high as 20 percent of college and high school females”. These implications a hard to ignore as they affect society's youth in extremely difficult ways. 
One of the most frequent post-feminist beauty myths is a social media trend that happened in 2021 that is called “Strong is the new skinny” according to Jessica Maddox with the Feminist Media Studies. According to the article, “given postfeminist contradictions, this presents a terrain in which only certain women are even allowed to attempt to achieve the unobtainable body”. This trend gives a new face to the beauty myth and can be just as destructive as the beauty myth that started it all. This social media trend “repackages old body stereotypes in a way befitting the era of postfeminist confidence”. There has been a re-emergence of beauty myths located within social media trends. However, as stated in the article, some of these trends are “worth noting as feminism turns to the fourth wave and emphasizes hashtags-hashtags can turn and remain rhetorical if not critically probed”.
As we’ve discussed the beauty myth in this paper, we have gotten a deeper look into how it affects us as a society. Whether it be social media trends, eating disorders, or incomes it can affect us all. It is a societal standard that is prevalent in the past and today that can control how we think about ourselves and how we act in society. It is a long-standing standard that needs to change and can be very detrimental to mental health. Hopefully, in the future the beauty myth will be irrelevant to society.
